Recap

  • Non-owning
  • Contiguous memory
  • Zero length/null handling
  • Can be used in constexpr context

Some helper functions

Generating constants

template <typename T, std::size_t S, typename F>                                       
constexpr std::array<T, S> make_constexpr_array(F&& f) {   
    std::array<T, S> result;                                                           
    f(std::span(result));                                                              
    return result;                                                                     
}                                                                                      

constexpr auto constant_signal = make_constexpr_array<float, 100>(whatever_function);

Generating constants

constexpr void make_ramp(std::span<int32_t> output) {        
    for (std::size_t i = 0; i < output.size(); i++) {                      
        output[i] = i;                                                     
    }                                                                      
}                                                                          

constexpr auto int32_ramp = make_constexpr_array<int32_t, 10>(make_ramp);   
static_assert(int32_ramp[6] == 6);

Generating constants

struct ramp_t {                                                                       
    template <typename T, std::size_t S>                                              
    constexpr void operator()(std::span<T, S> output) const {           
        for (std::size_t i = 0; i < output.size(); i++) {                             
            output[i] = T(i);                                                         
        }                                                                             
    }                                                                                 
};                                                                                    
constexpr ramp_t ramp;                                                                

constexpr auto float_ramp = make_constexpr_array<float, 10>(ramp);
static_assert(float_ramp[2] == 2.0);

Generating constants

template <typename T, std::size_t S>
constexpr auto t_ramp = make_constexpr_array<T, S>(ramp);

static_assert(t_ramp<int8_t, 10>[7] == 7);

Ownership

std::span is great, as now the user has the ability to choose how or where to allocate, but as a drawback now the user has to know (and care) about buffers he will not use directly.

Ownership

An example

template <typename T, std::size_t S>                               
constexpr void bartlett_window(std::span<const T, S> in,
                               std::span<T, S> out) {            
    auto weights = /* ??? */;                                      
    for (std::size_t i = 0; i < size; i++) {                       
        out[i] = weights[i] * in[i];                               
    }                                                              
}                                                                  

bartlett_window(in, out);

We can write very generic functions with templates.

Templating the size allows us to capture the user intent easily and we give the user a clue on the size requirements of the buffers.

It's not this bad for a user to manage input output buffers, considering that as library authors we don't know how those buffers will be used.

Forcing a choice

template <typename T, std::size_t S>
constexpr void bartlett_window(std::span<const T, S> in, 
                               std::span<T, S> out) {
    constexpr auto size = in.size();                       
    T* storage = new T[size]();              
    bartlett(std::span<T, S>(storage, size));              

    auto weights = std::span<const T, S>(storage, size);
    for (std::size_t i = 0; i < size; i++) {
        out[i] = weights[i] * in[i];
    }
    delete[] storage;                                      
}

I cannot use std::unique_ptr or any other smart pointer as it has non-constexpr constructors/destructors. P2273 will let us.

Buck passing

                      std::span<T, S> out) {

The user should not be dealing with implementation details

Hiding implementation

template <typename T, std::size_t S = std::dynamic_extent>     
struct window_t {
    T weights[S];                                                              

    constexpr window_t(auto f) {                                   
        f(std::span(weights));                                   
    }                                                                          

    constexpr void operator()(std::span<const T, S> in, 
                              std::span<T, S> out) const {                   
        for (int i = 0; i < in.size(); i++) {                                  
            out[i] = weights[i] * in[i];                                       
        }                                                                      
    }                                                                          
};

std::dynamic_extent is a constant that signals that the span's size is not known at compile-time. It can be leveraged to overload this struct to allow for dynamic memory usage.

Using it as a default template parameter adds up for a nice interface, where the user specifies the size only when it's known.

Hiding implementation

template <typename T>
struct window_t<T, std::dynamic_extent> {
    std::unique_ptr<T[]> weights;
    std::size_t size;                                                                      

    window_t(auto f, std::size_t size)  : weights(new T[size]), size(size) {   
        f(std::span(weights.get(), size));                                                 
    }                                                                                      

    void operator()(std::span<const T> in, std::span<T> out) const {
        for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
            out[i] = weights[i] * in[i];
        }
    }
};

Combining algorithms

Algorithms alone seldom solve a real problem.

Following our example, what would happen if we tried to combine the above windowing function with another algorithm like FFT (WFT)?

Combining algorithms

template <typename T, std::size_t S>                   
struct windowed_spectrum_t {
    window_t<T, S> window;                             
    spectrum_t<T, S> spectrum;                         
    T temp[S]; // <-- A temporary buffer is used as a bridge!

    windowed_spectrum_t(auto fn) : window(fn) { }     

    constexpr void operator()(std::span<const T, S> in,
                              std::span<T, S> out) {   
        window(in, temp);           
        spectrum(temp, out);        
    }                                                  
};

Temporary buffers
should be shared

Another algorithm

template <typename T>                                              
static constexpr void dct_transform(std::span<T> out,              
                                    std::span<T> temp);            

template <typename T, std::size_t S>                               
struct dct_t {                                                     
    T temp[S]; // <-- another buffer!                           

    constexpr void operator()(std::span<const T, S> in,
                              std::span<T, S> out) {             
        std::copy(in.begin(), in.end(), out.begin());              
        dct_transform<T>(out, temp);       
    }                                                              
};

The idea

stateDiagram-v2 ComposedAlgorithm --> Algorithm1 ComposedAlgorithm --> Algorithm2 ComposedAlgorithm --> Algorithm3 ComposedAlgorithm --> Algorithm4 Algorithm1 --> Buffer1 Algorithm2 --> Buffer1 Algorithm2 --> Buffer2 Algorithm3 --> Buffer1 Algorithm3 --> Buffer2 Algorithm3 --> Buffer3

Important thing: each algorithm does not run in parallel. One can compose (and share buffers) based on stages of the application and not based on algorithms themselves.

Modelling a buffer

template <auto tag, typename T, std::size_t S = std::dynamic_extent>
struct buffer_t {
    inline operator std::span<T, S>() { return storage; }  
private:                                                   
    T storage[S];                                          
};

Modelling a buffer

template <auto tag, typename T>
struct buffer_t<tag, T, std::dynamic_extent> {
    buffer_t(std::size_t size): storage(new T[size]), size(size) { }         

    inline operator std::span<T>() { return { storage.get(), size }; }     
private:                                                                   
    std::unique_ptr<T[]> storage;                                          
    std::size_t size;                                                      
};

Modelling a buffer

A little helper

template <auto tag, typename T, std::size_t S>
std::span<T, S> get_buffer(buffer_t<tag, T, S>* buffer) {
    return *buffer;
}

Virtual non-virtual inheritance

constexpr struct {} transform_tag;                                 

template <typename T, std::size_t S = std::dynamic_extent>
struct dct_t : private virtual buffer_t<transform_tag, T, S> {
    using buffer_t<transform_tag, T, S>::buffer_t;                 

    constexpr void dct(std::span<const T, S> in,
                       std::span<T, S> out) {
        std::copy(in.begin(), in.end(), out.begin());
        dct_transform<T>(out, get_buffer<transform_tag>(this));
    }
};

Virtual non-virtual inheritance

template <typename T, std::size_t S>
struct windowed_spectrum_t : private virtual buffer_t<transform_tag, T, S>  {
    window_t<T, S> window;
    spectrum_t<T, S> spectrum;

    /* ...constructors... */

    constexpr void windowed_spectrum(std::span<const T, S> in,
                               std::span<T, S> out) {
        window(in, get_buffer<transform_tag>(this));                
        spectrum(get_buffer<transform_tag>(this), out);             
    }
};

Virtual non-virtual inheritance

template <typename T, std::size_t S>
struct algorithms_t:
    windowed_spectrum_t<T, S>,
    dct_t<T, S>
{
    constexpr algorithms(auto fn) 
            requires (S != std::dynamic_extent): 
        windowed_spectrum_t<T, S>(fn),
        dct_t<T, S>() { } 

    constexpr algorithms(auto fn, std::size_t size) 
            requires (S == std::dynamic_extent): 
        windowed_spectrum_t<T, S>(fn, size),
        dct_t<T, S>(size) { } 
};

Virtual non-virtual inheritance

algorithms_t<float, 1024> algorithms(bartlett);        

void run_static() {
    float input[1024], output[1024];                   

    for (;;) {
        read_samples(input);                           

        algorithms.dct(input, output);                 
        write_usart(output);                           

        algorithms.windowed_spectrum(input, output);   
        write_leds(output);                            
    }
}

Virtual non-virtual inheritance

void run_stack() {
    algorithms_t<float, 1024> algorithms(bartlett);    
    float input[1024], output[1024];                   

    for (;;) {
        read_samples(input);                           

        algorithms.dct(input, output);                 
        write_usart(output);                         

        algorithms.windowed_spectrum(input, output);   
        write_leds(output);                            
    }
}

Virtual non-virtual inheritance

void run_dynamic(std::size_t size) {
    algorithms_t<float> algorithms(bartlett, size);    
    std::vector<float> 
        input(1024), output(1024);                          

    for (;;) {
        read_samples(input);                           

        algorithms.dct(input, output);                 
        write_usart(output);                         

        algorithms.windowed_spectrum(input, output);   
        write_leds(output);                            
    }
}
